doc.ContractDescription: THE MASSACHUSETTS SPACE GRANT CONSORTIUM (MASGC) COMPRISES OF ACADEMIC AND INFORMAL EDUCATION INSTITUTIONS ACROSS THE STATE. THE GOALS OF MASGC ARE: TO SUPPORT THE NATIONAL SPACE GRANT AGENDA TO DEVELOP A STRONG SCIENCE, MATHEMATICS AND TECHNOLOGY EDUCATION BASE FROM ELEMENTARY THROUGH UNIVERSITY LEVELS. TO PROMOTE SPACE-RELATED RESEARCH, EDUCATION, BUSINESS OPPORTUNITIES, AND PUBLIC SERVICE IN MASSACHUSETTS. TO RECRUIT AND TRAIN STUDENTS OF ALL AGES FOR CAREERS IN AERONAUTICS, SPACE SCIENCE, AND RELATED TECHNOLOGIES. TO ENCOURAGE WOMEN, MINORITIES AND PERSONS WITH DISABILITIES TO PURSUE THEIR INTEREST IN AEROSPACE. TO INCREASE PUBLIC AWARENESS AND APPRECIATION OF NASA ACTIVITIES. TO MEET THE ABOVE GOALS, MASGC ADDED 3 NEW AFFILIATE MEMBERS DURING THE LAST 5-YEAR GRANT CYCLE, INCLUDING 2 COMMUNITY COLLEGES SERVING MINORITIES AND ECONOMICALLY UNDERPRIVILEGED POPULATIONS. THE CONSORTIUM WILL CONTINUE TO WORK WITH THEM AND EXPAND PROGRAMS WITH THE COMMUNITY COLLEGES. IN THE LAST FIVE YEARS, THE CONSORTIUM INCREASED FELLOWSHIP AWARDS FROM 9 TO 90, ANNUALLY. THE CONSORTIUM HAD A TOTAL OF 191 PARTICIPANTS IN RESEARCH PROGRAMS, 1057 IN HIGHER EDUCATION PROGRAMS, 5806 IN PRE-COLLEGE PROGRAMS AND 2946 IN PROGRAMS FOR THE GENERAL PUBLIC. THE CONSORTIUM PLANS TO CONTINUE TO SUPPORT THESE PROGRAMS AND ADD NEW PROGRAMS SUCH AS THE ZERO ROBOTICS PROGRAM, ENGINEERING IN THE EI-HI CURRICULUM, AND ASTRONOMY AND SPACE IN THE CLASSROOM (DESCRIBED IN SECTION 0.4). THE NUMBER OF AFFLLIATES RECEIVING AWARDS HAS CONSISTENTLY INCREASED, FROM FIVE IN THE FIRST YEAR TO THIRTEEN IN THE FIFTH YEAR OF THE LAST GRANT CYCLE. THE CONSORTIUM WILL CONTINUE TO ENCOURAGE THIS WIDE PARTICIPATION FROM ITS AFFILIATES IN THE NEXT CYCLE. MASGC HAS WORKED HARD TO MEET NASA'S DIVERSITY GOALS. DURING THE LAST FIVE YEARS, 44,8% OF ALL FELLOWSHIP AND SCHOLARSHIP AWARDS WENT TO FEMALES. 51% OF OUR RESEARCH PROGRAM PARTICIPANTS WERE WOMEN AS WERE 40% OF OUR HIGHER EDUCATION PROGRAM PARTICIPANTS. 13.6% OF OUR FELLOWSHIP/SCHOLARSHIP SUPPORT DURING THE REPORTING PERIOD WENT TO UNDERREPRESENTED MINORITIES, AS DID 14% OF OUR RESEARCH INFRASTRUCTURE SUPPORT, AND 27% OF OUR HIGHER EDUCATION SUPPORT. 61% OF THE TEACHERS MASGC SUPPORTED FOR STEM TRAINING ACTIVITIES WERE WOMEN, AND 22% WERE UNDERREPRESENTED MINORITIES. THESE PERCENTAGES MEET (WITHIN STATISTICAL MARGINS) OR EXCEED THE 15% FIGURE REPORTED FOR MASSACHUSETTS BY THE NATIONAL CENTER OF EDUCATION STATISTICS (EXCLUDING ASIANS), WHICH IS OUR OFFICIALLY MANDATED GOAL. IN 2007, MASGC INITIATED A PROGRAM WITH THE PERKINS SCHOOL FOR THE BLIND, WITH LECTURES ON SPACE AND SUPPORT FOR WORKSHOPS TO TRAIN TEACHERS IN PRESENTING STEM MATERIAL TO STUDENTS WITH DISABILITIES. IN THE NEXT GRANT CYCLE, THE CONSORTIUM IS PLANNING TO INVITE PERKINS TO BECOME A FULL-FLEDGED AFFILIATE IN ORDER TO INCREASE SUPPORT FOR STUDENTS WITH DISABILITIES.
